author: Kate_Marvel;
title: Can clouds buy us more time to solve climate change?

aws-transcripts.transcript: I am a climate scientist and I hate weather. I have spent too much time in California, and I strongly feel that weather should be optional. So I don't want to experience clouds, let alone study them. But clouds seem to follow me wherever I go. The thing is, how is a real challenge for climate science? We don't know how they're gonna react as the planet heats up and hidden in that uncertainty might be hope. Maybe, just maybe, clouds could slow down global warming and buy us a little bit more time to get our act together, which would be very convenient right now. I mean, even I could put up with a few more cloudy days if clouds save the planet. Now we are sure about some things. Carbon dioxide is a greenhouse gas were emitting a lot of it and plan. It's heating up, case closed. But I still go to work every day. It turns out that there is a lot that we don't understand about climate change. In particular, we haven't answered what seems to be a very fundamental question. We know it's gonna get hot, but we don't know exactly how hot it's gonna get now, this is a really easy question to answer if one of you would like to give me a time machine, but I'm gonna be honest with you. If I had a time machine, I would not be hanging out at this particular point in history. So in order to see the future, we have to rely on the output of computer simulation Jin's climate models like this one. Now, in my line of work, I encounter many very charming people on the Internet who liked to tell me that climate models are all wrong, and I would just like to say no kidding. Seriously, I get paid to complain about climate models, but we don't want models to be perfect. We want them to be useful. I mean, think about it. A computer simulation that's able to exactly reproduce all of reality. That's not a climate model. That's the Matrix. So models are not crystal balls, their research tools and the ways in which they're wrong can actually teach us a lot. For example, different climate models are largely able to capture the warming that we've seen so far, but fast forward to the end of the century under a business as usual scenario. And climate models don't really agree anymore. Yeah, they're all warming. That's just basic physics. But some of thumb project catastrophe more than five times the warming we've seen already, and others are literally more chill. So why don't climate models agree on how warm it's gonna get? Well, to a large extent, it's because they don't agree on what clouds will do in the future. And that is because, just like me, computers hate clouds, computers hate clouds because they're simultaneously very large and very small. Clouds are formed when microscopic water droplets are ice crystals coalesce around tiny particles, but at the same time, they cover 2/3 of the Earth's surface. In order to really accurately model clouds, we need to track the behavior of every water droplet and dust, grain and the entire it's here, and there's no computer powerful enough to do that. So instead we have to make a trade off. We can zoom in and get the details right, but have no idea what's going on worldwide. Or we could sacrifice realism at small scales in order to see the bigger picture. Now there's no one right Answer. No perfect way to do this. And different climate models make different choices. Now it It is unfortunate that computer struggle with clouds because clouds air crucially important in regulating the temperature of the planet. In fact, if all the clouds went away, we would experience profound climate changes. But without clouds, would it be warmer or colder? The answer is both. So I'm gonna be honest with you. I am not a cloud spotter. My favorite type of cloud is none, but even I know that clouds come in all shapes and sizes. Low, thick clouds like these are really good at blocking out the sun and ruining your barbecue. And high, wispy clouds like these Serious largely let that sunlight stream through.
